  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a very real concern that I've observed in my grandchildren's schooling. When they're told they're 'not good at math,' it affects their confidence, even if they're capable. I remember my own school days in Bari, where girls were often discouraged from pursuing science subjects, and that made me anxious about my own abilities. This fear of being judged by stereotypes can hold back many young minds. We should address it by creating inclusive environments where every child feels valued, not just by their gender or background. For example, schools could have more female role models in STEM fields, showing kids that women and girls can excel in these areas. Also, teachers should be trained to recognize and counteract stereotype threat before it takes root. In my quiet moments, I often think about how important it is to nurture each child's potential without letting biases cloud their future. As a retired teacher who spent years in the classroom, I know that small, consistent efforts can make a big difference. The key is to be patient and compassionate, understanding that every child has a unique path to success. We must work together to ensure that no one is held back by what others think they should be.",
